title: Student Exhibition Opening at the Nasher
details: Join MUSE at the student opening of the Nasher's new exhibition featuring the works of Ebony G. Patterson. Featuring musical performances by local and student artists. Desserts and refreshments provided. Smart-casual attire encouraged.About the exhibition:Ebony G. Patterson . . . while the dew is still on the roses . . . presents the work of artist Ebony G. Patterson, born in Jamaica in 1981. This is the most significant exhibition of the artist's work to date, presented within a new installation environment that evokes a night garden.Patterson is known for drawings, tapestries, videos, sculptures and installations that involve surfaces layered with flowers, glitter, lace and beads. Her work investigates forms of embellishment as they relate to youth culture within disenfranchised communities. Her neo-baroque works address violence, masculinity, "bling," visibility and invisibility within the post-colonial context of her native Kingston and within black youth culture globally. This exhibition focuses on the role that gardens have played in her practice, referenced as spaces of both beauty and burial, environments filled with fleeting aesthetics and mourning.Food Provided

title: Duke China-U.S. Summit (DCUS) 2020
details: Duke China-U.S. Summit (DCUS) 2020 centers around the theme of "Beyond 2020: China-U.S. Relations in the New Decade". As China-U.S. relations enter a new era of rising speculation and competition, DCUS 2020 seeks to engage experts, commentators and professionals across industries to discuss emerging opportunities for China and the U.S. to maintain a mutually beneficial relationship. Panel discussions will focus on multiple areas including but not limited to academic cooperation, technological innovations, and sustainable development.

title: Value of Water
details: As water variability continues to become a concerning issue around the world, how do we interpret the value we place on water resources? How are impacts quantified at fisheries, mitigation banks, or water authorities? Companies are beginning to focus on the concept of water risk, the impacts of too little or too much water, and rapidly developing technological solutions. This symposium will include discussions about the economic valuation of water resources and how water is intrinsically impacted during resource extraction activities designed to derive value out of natural resources. During this one day symposium, you will learn from professionals in the field to see how businesses, government, and academia approach quantifying the value of water!

title: The Place of the Altar and the Shape of the Font: Theological Readings of Early Christian Liturgical Spaces
details: The design, decoration, and spatial location of these two central elements of early churches provide concrete evidence for how early Christians would have practiced, experienced and theologically comprehended the eucharistic and baptismal sacraments. This lecture will integrate archeological remains from both East and West with textual sources to illuminate the symbolic, sensory, and spiritual experience of lived Christian practice in antiquity and, finally, explore ways the contemporary Church has drawn upon these resources for liturgical renewal.

title: Why the Catholic Church Is Not Pacifist: Understanding the Church's View on War and Peace

The talk will discuss alternative views on force, including pacifism, and explain that peacemaking sometimes involves the judicious use of force against those who upset peace

title: Global Implications of Racism in US Foreign Policy
details: American political leaders have largely approached civil rights issues and diplomacy separately. In the context of a renewed movement for racial justice, this conversation with Professor Deonte Harris and AHS President Mohammad Khatami will explore the intersectionality of the two topics by analyzing how American racism has shaped political, social, and economic development around the world. The discussion will detail the origin of institutional racism within American foreign policy and how it has harmed people of color around the world. We will also consider America's evolving role in the world and whether the nation can or should use its military and diplomatic influence to promote global racial equity.

title: Duke China-U.S. Summit 2021: Shared Struggles In U.S.-China Relations
details: Themed "Rebuilding 2021: Shared Struggles in U.S.-China Relations", the Duke China- US Summit in 2021 situates at a historical tipping point. Although political, economic, and social tensions between China and the United States continue to rise, in the context of a global pandemic China and the U.S. will each play a vital role, and the future of the relationship will largely shape the future of the globe. DCUS 2021 seeks to engage scholars, experts and professionals from many sectors to consider a future of constructive U.S.-China partnership. Conversations will cross disciplines, discussing public health, novel technology, education, culture and society to ultimately explore creative ways of rebuilding a future of mutual understanding and collaboration. This involves various formats including panel discussions, workshops, career fairs, and a novel case competition that pinpoints key issues in the China-U.S. relations. The summit is going virtual this year, reaching a global audience via creative ways of engagements.File Attachments:

title: Piloting Your Career in Washington, D.C. - Navigating Uncertainty in the Job Search
details: Finding your first job or internship can be daunting. How can I start building my network, learn about an industry that is new to me, or apply for a position with an unclear application process? While certain industries can have less structured recruiting timelines, it doesn’t mean you should shy away from a career path that speaks to your interests.During this event, a panel of career professionals will share advice on job searching in Washington, DC and what you can expect. title: Other Careers in Healthcare Panel
details: If you're considering a career in healthcare but aren't sure whether medical school is right for you, join us for our virtual panel about other careers in healthcare. The panel will feature a pharmacy resident, physical therapist, dentist, occupational therapist, physician assistant, and nurse practitioner. The panel provides a unique opportunity to engage in conversation with professionals from several health disciplines and hear about their work. In addition, the panelists will talk about the paths you can take to pursue these professions and how Duke University itself offers numerous programs in these disciplines. Come on out and explore the various practices in healthcare available outside the scope of medical school!

title: Exploring Careers Across Industries: Technology
details: Join us for an opportunity to connect with technology industry professionals (most of them Duke Alumni) to learn about the state of the industry and emerging trends, types of organizations/employers and what tech and non-tech roles exist, all while you explore career paths that align with your interests, skills and values.Registration and Zoom link in.

title: Building a Career in the Music Industry

title: The Syrian Civil War: A Humanitarian Crisis
details: Following the Arab Spring uprisings of 2011, political dissent in Syria quickly spiraled into a violent and devastating civil conflict. Since May 2012, the United States has been directly involved in this conflict, providing military and financial intervention against the Assad regime. In the next Alexander Hamilton Society event, we will be exploring the Syrian Civil War and the associated refugee crisis while also discussing the future of American involvement in the Middle East. Join the Alexander Hamilton Society on January 28 at 6 PM ET for a panel discussion featuring Duke professors Abdullah Antepli, Miriam Cooke, and Bruce Jentleson and The Ohio State University's Peter Mansoor. Future foreign policy leaders must understand what precipitated and deepened the societal fractures in Syria to better prevent similar conflicts and crises from developing in the region.

title: RecTalks | Staying Active Through a Pandemic
details: The benefits of physical activity and exercise have shown to be an important element to our overall well-being. Our bodies are designed to move and we gain a multitude of benefits through physical activity. COVID-19 has impacted and challenged our lives in many different ways, including how we exercise and recreate. Join our panel of experts to discuss how we have created diverse opportunities for fitness and recreation, both in-person and at-home..ABOUT RECTALKSRecTalks are informative and influential discussions with experts in their industries of sport, recreation, physical education and wellness. Hosted by Duke Recreation and Physical Education, our goal is to provide our community with resources and information that promotes the physical, environmental, and mental wellbeing of our university community.FUTURE RECTALK TOPICSDiversity in the OutdoorsNutritionMental WellbeingDiversity in Recreation & SportsPsychology in SportsTechnology

title: Winter Break Career Event

The career center also put on a cover letter workshop, and Nic school professors did virtual lunches with students. All those who attended an event were awarded with a $5 gift card to a local coffee shop. Those who attended morethan 3 events were entered a giveaway to get a $100 gift card.

title: Conversation with the CEO of NAMI (National Alliance on Mental Illness)
details: ┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡┬¡Join the Office of Community Engagement and Inclusion with Duke's Fuqua School of Business and DuWell with Duke Student Affairs for a conversation with the CEO of NAMI* (National Alliance on Mental Illness), Dan Gillison, on Tuesday, December 8th from 6:00 to 6:45 p.m.In this fireside chat, Dan will cover topics around mental health and mental health conditions, NAMI initiatives dedicated to decreasing stigma and increasing awareness, and ways to support the mental health of members of the Duke community, particularly those that are part of marginalized communities.Dan will also discuss the necessity for leaders to create an inclusive environment in which mental health is a priority.  He will do a deep dive into the importance of providing the tools and support employees need (and what those tools and support look like) to thrive in their professional and personal lives.For more information and to register, please go to the following link: https://bit.ly/NAMI_at_Duke.

title: RecTalks | The Power of the Outdoors
details: There is truly something to be said about the power of the outdoors and what it can do for us both physically and mentally. For many it can give us a sense of belonging, a sense of gratitude, and a sense of healing. However, access to outdoor spaces looks different for many people and has changed significantly due to COVID. Join us as we discuss the Power of the Outdoors and explore how we can use the outdoors to fight the impacts of stress and isolation, while working to be better advocates for our natural world and access to these spaces..ABOUT RECTALKSRecTalks are informative and influential discussions with experts in their industries of sport, recreation, physical education and wellness. Hosted by Duke Recreation and Physical Education, our goal is to provide our community with resources and information that promotes the physical, environmental, and mental wellbeing of our university community.FUTURE RECTALK TOPICSNutritionMental WellbeingDiversity in Recreation & SportsPsychology in SportsTechnology

title: Migration Policy in LAC
details: The number of migrants and refugees from Venezuela has reached virtually every country in the region. In parallel, Central and North America experience mixed migration movements of people from Central America, African, Asian and Caribbean countries trying to reach the US. Governments of the region have responded in different ways. Some have adopted an open border policy, imposed increasing restrictions on the migrant's mobility, and others have put safe third country agreements.The panel will discuss the landscape of migration in LAC and the innovative policy and private sector solutions to address and mitigate the effects of migration. The conference will also discuss the role of social and humanitarian organizations to support displaced people better.Speakers:Sarah Bermeo:  Political economist, associate professor of public policy and political science in the Sanford School at Duke University and director of graduate studies for the Master of International Development Policy (MIDP) program housed in the Duke Center for International Development. Her research lies at the intersection of international relations and development, with a particular focus on foreign aid, trade agreements, migration, and the global public good.Rachel Schmidtke: Advocate for Latin America at Refugees International working on advocacy strategies responding to the Central American and Venezuelan crisis. Previously, she was a program associate at the Mexico Institute of the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars developing the migration portfolio and producing policy work on Mexico, Central America, and U.S. migration, asylum, and refugee policy. Rachel received her M.A. in International Development Policy from Duke University, focusing on migration, Latin American foreign policy, and gender.Erik Wibbels: Co-Director of DevLab@Duke at Duke University. His research focuses on development, redistribution and political geography and has been published by Cambridge University Press, World Politics, International Organization, American Political Science Review and other journals. Current major projects include a USAID-funded effort to integrate machine learning, forecasting and rigorous field interventions to early-identify government crackdowns on civil society an a research with Te Conecta and RTI International on how the deportation of Guatemalans from the U.S. impacts households and communities on both sides of the border, as well as large field projects on local policing in Ghana and Guatemala.
host: Sanford Latin American and Caribbean Student Group

title: Disaster & Resilience DWN Fall Symposium
details: Thank you for your interest in Duke Water Network's (DWN) Fall Symposium. This year's theme of "Disaster and Resilience" highlights strategies that are being used to adapt and build more resilient communities in the face of water-related disasters and climate extremes.We are excited to present an opportunity for members of the Duke community to engage in the pivotal and timely discussions surrounding resiliency planning and recovery and to connect with speakers from Cape Fear Public Utility, the University of North Carolina Environmental Science Center, and the North Carolina Office of Recovery and Resiliency. A community's ability to respond and recover from disasters such as flooding and drought requires complex and interwoven policies and procedures. We wish to highlight and discuss the financial implications, legal avenues, and infrastructure preparedness required to face these challenges, and the implications they have for communitiesThe "Disaster and Response" Symposium will feature a morning Keynote session, an afternoon panel discussion highlighting ongoing adaptation and response strategies in North Carolina, and a networking social following the conclusion of the Symposium.

title: Alexander Hamilton Society Panel on the Crisis in Afghanistan
details: The human toll of the Taliban's displacement of Afghani communities has been lost in the coverage of America's withdrawal from Afghanistan. Tens of thousands of refugees are expected to reach the US in the next few weeks, and a half a million more are predicted to flee the country by the end of the year. After decades of investment, the international community remains unequipped to address the current crisis. How can the United States use its diplomatic and economic resources to provide safety to those fleeing the violence of their homeland?Join the Alexander Hamilton Society on September 30th at 6 PM ET for a panel discussion featuring the President/CEO of Lutheran Immigration and Refugee Services, Krish Vignarajah, and Duke professor and religious scholar, Abdullah Antepli.Everyone is welcome.

title: North Carolina Autistic Career Summit
details: The North Carolina Autistic Career Summit is for students and alumni on the autism spectrum who are seeking helpful tips and best practices for the job search process, and an opportunity to meet with employers recruiting for paid internships and degree-related full-time roles. In alignment with the concept of neurodiversity, the summit centers autistic voices and hosts sessions predominantly featuring a diverse array of autistic professionals from a variety of careers.In 2019 and 2020, the summit featured a combined total of 110+ students representing over 20 different institutions throughout NC and neighboring states. Whether community college, 4-year university, vocational or certificate program, this event is open for all to attend—not just NC State University students.

title: Data Science & Public Policy with Dr. Angel Hsu
details: Angel Hsu is an Assistant Professor of Public Policy and the Environment, Ecology and Energy Program (E3P). She is also Founder and Director of the Data-Driven EnviroLab, an interdisciplinary research group that innovates and applies quantitative approaches to pressing environmental issues. Her research explores the intersection of science and policy and the use of data-driven approaches to understand environmental sustainability, particularly in the areas of climate change and energy, urbanization and air quality. Her research projects apply large-scale datasets derived from satellite remote sensing and other spatially-explicit sources to evaluate environmental policy performance.

title: Alexander Hamilton Society Tigray Event
details: In November 2020, conflict between the government of Ethiopia and local militias erupted in the northern region of Tigray. In the year since, the military campaign has spiraled into a humanitarian crisis and raised fears of regional instability. The current situation is dire. Forces on the ground—Ethiopia's military, Eritrean troops, and Tigrayan forces—are responsible for sexual violence, ethnically targeted attacks, and large-scale looting. The United Nations estimates that nearly three million Tigrayans urgently need assistance.The path forward will require international cooperation, careful diplomacy, and an inclusive political process that restores confidence among the country's diverse population of 110 million.To better understand this complicated conflict, join the Alexander Hamilton Society and the Duke Ethiopian/Eritrean Student Transnational Association (DESTA) on January 27th at 6:30 PM ET for a panel discussion featuring Dr. Girma, Dr. Beshah, and Dr. Hino.

title: Africa Policy Talks
details: This this first edition of "Africa Policy Talks" coincides with the last day of the 27th Climate Summit (COP27), being hosted by Egypt (6th to 18th November). The COP27 agenda is focused around Climate Finance, Adaptation Efforts, Loss and Damage, and Increased Ambition. COP27 represents an opportunity for Africa to take center stage in shaping global climate negotiations to be better representative of Global South realities and needs. Africa Policy Talks seeks to facilitate dialogue between students and experts (within and outside the Duke community). We will discuss highlights from deliberations at COP27, climate action best practices from various contexts, opportunities for action and capacity development priorities.The Paris Agreement, adopted at COP21 in 2015, set a global goal to limit global warming to below 2 degree Celsius (1.5 preferably), compared to pre-industrial levels. At COP15 in 2009, developed countries pledged $100 billion annually in climate finance to developing countries by 2020. The timeline was extended to 2025 at COP21 in Paris. Till date, this target has never been met. No one feels these impacts more acutely than the more than 3.3 billion people living in countries highly vulnerable to climate change. The African continent is facing worsening economic conditions and consequences of the climate crisis – from deadly floods to crop-withering droughts – which are resulting in human displacements and huge humanitarian burdens. This is all happening despite being responsible for only 3% of carbon emissions. Meanwhile, over 750 million Africans lack access to electricity - while food insecurity, rising fuel prices, and increasing loss and damages put lives at risk.
location: Sanford 09, Sanford School of Public Policy

Dr. Farmer, a Duke alumnus and former Trustee, devoted his life to addressing global health disparities in locations across the globe. Learn about his life and legacy and how Duke is continuing to address those disparities. Panelists include:Dr. Chris Beyrer, the new Director of the Global Health InstituteDr. Bailor Barrier, the Executive Director of Partners in Health Sierra LeoneDr. Adia Benton, Associate Professor of Anthropology, Northwestern UniversityJade Tso '19, Medical Student at UC Davis, Anne Carter Global Health FellowStudents and families are encouraged to watch Bending the Arc prior to the session. Bending The Arc tells the story of Paul Farmer and his colleagues who helped build Partner in Health and raise awareness around global health inequities.

title: PBS NC's Preview Screening of Facing Suicide and Discussion—Hybrid Event
details: HYBRID EVENT //Two ways to join: online or in person at the PBS North Carolina studioWednesday, August 31, at 7 PM: A special preview screening of Facing Suicide. The film explores powerful stories of those impacted by suicide—one of America's most urgent health crises—and journey to the front lines of research with scientists whose work is leading to better prevention and treatment.Following the screening, we invite you to participate in a conversation and audience Q&A with an esteemed group of local experts led by Dr. Carrie Brown, chief medical officer for behavioral health and intellectual and developmental disabilities, North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services. Audience participation is encouraged and you can ask the panelists questions either in person or online via the chat feature.IN-PERSON Event DetailsDate and Time: Wednesday, August 31, at 7 PMLocation: PBS North Carolina studio (10 UNC-TV Drive, Research Triangle Park)Screening of clips from PBS's Facing Suicide and Panel DiscussionVIRTUAL Event DetailsDate and Time: Wednesday, August 31, at 7 PMLocation: From the convenience of your own home, office, laptop, computer or mobile device. The event will be livestreamed from PBS North Carolina's studioScreening of clips from PBS's Facing Suicide and Panel discussionLink to join event can be found in your registration confirmation.Moderator: Dr. Carrie Brown, chief medical officer for behavioral health and intellectual and developmental disabilities, North Carolina Department of Health and Human ServicesPanelists:Dr. Vivian Barnette, executive director, Counseling Services, NC A&T UniversityCharnequa Kennedy, director, Counseling Center, North Carolina Central UniversityCamryn Hendrix, Peer2Peer student counselor, University of North Carolina at Chapel HillAshish George, director of public policy/psychiatric advance directives (PADs) specialist, NAMI NC (National Alliance on Mental Illness)Fonda Bryant, certified QPR (Question Persuade Refer) Suicide Prevention Instructor, Member-at-Large, NAMI NC Board of Directors and featured in the documentary, Facing SuicideDiscussion topics:suicide awareness and preventionmental health resourceshow and where to seek helpmessages of hopeThis is a FREE event, but registration is required. Please reserve your seat or your virtual ticket by registering via Eventbrite. In-person tickets are extremely limited and available on a first come basis. Questions? Email Karen Nowak at knowak@pbsnc.org.

title: Wrongfully Convicted
details: "Wrongfully Convicted" is a speaker event with the purpose of sparking conversation around policing, mass incarceration, and wrongful convictions. The event will feature John Bunn, a man who was wrongfully convicted of a murder he did not commit when he was only 14 years old. Mr. Bunn spent over 16 years in prison and nearly 12 on parole before he was exonerated. Now, as an activist, Mr. Bunn will share his inspiring story of how he overcame the failures of the criminal justice system and found purpose in life.Alongside Mr. Bunn, we will feature guest speakers including Kristin Henning, author and Georgetown Professor of Law; Kristen John Foy, President and CEO of the Arc of Justice; and Mark Anthony Neal, distinguished Duke Professor. Our speakers have expertise in the fields of law, activism, entrepreneurship, and academia and will provide unique insights to these complex issues in a panel conversation that you will not want to miss.

title: What Nobody Tells You: Offer Letters
details: Are you currently in the job market and are looking to begin applying, interviewing, and landing your next opportunity, soon? Each step of the job search is important, but perhaps what needs a more nuanced discussion is what happens when you receive your first job offer! Join the Duke Career Center and Lisa Lawson, JD (T' 89), as we discuss what nobody tells you about the offer letter. Register in Handshake!Lisa Lawson has over twenty-five years of practice in large-stakes employment disputes. She is a co-founding partner of a boutique women-owned law firm, named by SF Business Times as one of the Bay Area's 100 Largest Women-Owned Businesses. With extensive experience in employment litigation, counseling, training, and workplace investigations, she has served on the Executive Committee of the State Bar's Labor and Employment Law Section. Martindale Hubbell Peer Rated AV "Preeminent" and Northern California Super Lawyer. Her specialty areas include: All aspects of California and federal employment law, including discrimination law, employee privacy, wage-and-hour issues, and contract disputes. Extensive experience litigating employee mobility issues.

title: NC Neurodiversity College Career Summit
details: The virtual 2023 NC Neurodiversity College Career Summit connects NC college students pursuing degree-related (paid) internships and full-time opportunities with employers who are seeking to establish or maintain work environments supporting neurodiversity. The event includes both an informational panel session as well as opportunities for students to engage with employers regarding interests and opportunities.Our Focus: Neurodiversity is an inclusive term that emphasizes the abilities of people with "brain differences" that are distinct from what is considered "typical." As a social justice movement, neurodiversity aims to recognize the strengths and unique challenges of those with autism, ADHD and other neurological differences.

title: Karsh Conversations: Climate Careers
details: Karsh Conversations bring together current Duke students and alumni from a variety of industries for small-group dinners at the Karsh Alumni and Visitors Center for dynamic conversations and relationship-building. This series is open to all undergraduate, graduate, and professional school students enrolled at Duke, and students from all areas of study and backgrounds are welcome to attend the November 1 program. In this Conversation, we invite alumni in careers and spaces related to energy, environment, sustainability, and climate change with a wide range of applications. Students will chat with alumni speakers and learn about their paths in climate careers. Presented by Duke Alumni Engagement & Development and the Duke Career Center. Register on CVENT!

title: A2i Job Search Series
details: Accelerate to Industry (A2i) is an industry workforce readiness program for graduate students and postdoctoral researchers developed by the NC State University Graduate School. title: Envisioning Urban Futures Conference
details: We can only plan for the future we want if we imagine that future in the first place. Join us as we ask scientists, artists, engineers, writers and other experts from across the disciplines to outline the future that they think is most likely — a business as usual future — and then also the better future toward which they are working. In thinking about those better urban futures, scholars will consider beauty, sustainability and livability, among other urban elements. Throughout these presentations a focus will be placed on the recognition that the human story is embedded in the broader story of the living world, one part of a bigger whole.This event will feature a series of short, TED-style talks, as well as poster presentations by faculty, students and staff from around the world at the messy interface between cutting-edge research and big picture thinking. There will also be food and drink, music and artistic interpretations of envisioned urban futures.Food Provided

title: Brasa Summit 2023
details: The BRASA Summit is an annual event that brings together Brazilian students, professionals and leaders who are making significant differences, not just in Brazil, but around the world. Our purpose is to connect students to the Brazilian reality and discuss critical issues facing the country. Through interactive panels, initiatives, chats and debates, we promote the exchange of experiences and ideas between speakers and students. through initiatives and challanges we want to empower students to be prepared for the job market. BRASA's values, such as creating new opportunities, passion for transformation and commitment to Brazil, are highlighted and put into practice at the BRASA Summit. This year, we are excited to invite you to BRASA Summit 2023, which has "Legacy" as its theme. Our main goal is to inspire, develop and connect young people so that they believe in their abilities and are able to achieve what they want to leave as their legacy.

title: SPARK Conversation on Affirmative Action
details: In June of 2023, the U.S Supreme Court voted to curb affirmative action in higher education. Are you curious about what this could mean for diversity in higher education? For you? If you'd like to learn more about how the ruling impacts Duke and other institutions, join us for our SPARK Conversation on Monday, September 25th at 6pm in Dollard Commons (Kilgo P). Dinner provided for those who register on Duke Groups.Facilitated by Dr. Shruti Desai, Associate Vice President of Student Affairs for Student Engagement, the conversation will be your opportunity to participate in a meaningful discussion and gain a better sense of clarity on this landmark supreme court decision.  Register here: bit.ly/sparkconvoAA

title: Spark Summit 2023
details: Our annual Spark Summit is on Saturday, August 26th, before classes start!The Summit is an intentional space for grounding the Sophomore experience at Duke by providing opportunities for networking, hearing from alumni, a resource fair, and other sessions focused on wellness, advice, and mentorship. There will also be food, merch giveaways, raffles, and more! Our hope is that you will leave feeling empowered and equipped to tackle the Sophomore slump and other challenges you may face during your college journey, so register today. We hope to see you there!Register in Handshake and continue to check the Career Hub for updated details.
